<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-126-001 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 895 278  OV: 10 895 010.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  June 24 1991 v8 n25 p120(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus Development Corp.: Freelance Graphics for DOS 4.0. (SoftwareReview) (one of eight evaluations of presentation graphicssoftware in 'Presentation graphics ease chart creation.')andO;(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Halliday, Caroline.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Lotus Development Corp's $495 Freelance Graphics for DOS 4.0presentation graphics program is feature-rich but difficult touse.andP;  Users must wade through several interfaces in order tocreate charts, but there are no significant performance problems.andO;Lotus bundles the program with GrandView LT, a customized versionof Symantec Corp's GrandView outliner, for use in creating textcharts.andP;  Freelance Graphics for DOS makes less use of the mousethan competing products and suffers from a somewhat illogicalmouse interface.andP;  All menu choices are textual, and there areseparate screens for the graphics editor and for textual dataforms.andP;  The new WYSIWYG screen is nevertheless a major improvementover the previous version.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Product:   Freelance Graphics (Presentation software) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Presentation SoftwareSoftware PackagesEvaluation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Vital signs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Lotus Development Corp.andM;FREELANCE GRAPHICS FOR DOS 4.0andM;Although greatly improved in the latest version and rich with features,Freelance Graphics for DOS is hard to use.andP;  The chart-creation processrequires the use of one type of user interface, and drawing and refining achart requires another -- making chart creation unnecessarily cumbersome.andO;However, PC Week Labs experienced no performance problems using the product,and the output was satisfactory.andM;GrandView LT, a customized version of Symantec Corp.'s GrandView outliner, isincluded with Freelance for use in creating text charts.andP;  The spellingchecker is included in this module, not in Freelance itself.andP;  After textcharts are completed, they can be read directly by Freelance.andM;Freelance Graphics for DOS emphasizes keyboard use too much, and the mouseinterface isn't always logical.andP;  Scrolling through data forms, for example,is not smooth.andP;  Menu choices are textual.andP;  For example, a chart type isselected from a list rather than through pictorial representations.andM;Freelance has two main screen types: the graphics editor, where the currentchart is displayed, and the textual data forms screens, for setting chartoptions and entering data.andP;  Freelance switches between the two typesautomatically, as necessary.andM;The WYSIWYG screen and improved font features were essential improvements inthis version; however, the program lacks an organization-chart feature.andM;All parameters that affect the chart, such as colors in a bar chart or thesize of a chart, are set via the data forms screen.andM;The graphics editor is used to add the extra graphics information such asclip art and backgrounds.andP;  The graphics-editor screen has two pages: Thefirst is used to create the chart, and the second as a temporary clipboard toretrieve clip-art collections and select objects from them.andM;The drawing tool set is complete and includes line, arrow, rectangle,polygon, circle, arc, text and freehand drawing tools.andM;Editing and object placement is easy with tools such as snapping, aligningand grouping.andM;------------------&quot;VITAL SIGNS&quot; DATAandM;Lotus Development Corp.andM;Cambridge, Mass.andP;  (617) 577-8500andM;Publicly heldandM;Year established: 1982andM;Number of employees: 3,538andM;Gross annual revenue (1990): $684.5 millionandM;Net annual income (1990): $23.3 million Source.andP;  Information supplied bycompany.andM;</TEXT></DOC>